            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> This variant is the fastest, faster may only be something using pyeval/luaeval/…. :grep may find loads of things which have nothing to do with the requested branch:\n\nMaybe I should have been more clear, but I've updated the first post to show\n\n``` vim\nlet branch = grepfile(\".git/packed-refs\", \"refs/remotes/{remote-name}/{branch-name}$\")\n```\n\nThe version using `filter()` takes about 0.2 seconds on my computer, whereas using `grepfile()`, it take 0.04 with `&grepprg = \"grep -n $* /dev/null\"`. `readfile()` copies the whole file to a linked list, then `filter()` has to traverse this list and interpret the predicate. By comparison, grepping involves much less work.\n",
